# DevOps and CI/CD

## Objective

Learn the basics of DevOps and Continuous Integration/Continuous Deployment (CI/CD), understand their workflow, benefits, and commonly used tools.

---

## What is DevOps?

DevOps is a software development approach that brings together the **Development (Dev)** and **Operations (Ops)** teams. It focuses on collaboration, automation, and continuous improvement to develop, test, and deploy applications faster and more reliably.

---

## DevOps Lifecycle

1. Plan
2. Develop
3. Build
4. Test
5. Release
6. Deploy
7. Operate
8. Monitor

This lifecycle helps teams deliver software continuously with better quality.

---

## What is CI/CD?

CI/CD stands for **Continuous Integration** and **Continuous Deployment (or Continuous Delivery)**.

### Continuous Integration (CI)

Continuous Integration is the practice of automatically building and testing code whenever developers make changes.

**Benefits:**
- Detects bugs early
- Improves code quality
- Reduces integration issues
- Enables faster development

### Continuous Delivery (CD)

Continuous Delivery ensures that the application is always ready for deployment after passing all tests.

**Benefits:**
- Faster software releases
- Reduced deployment risks
- Reliable release process

### Continuous Deployment

Continuous Deployment automatically deploys every successful code change to production without manual intervention.

---

## CI/CD Workflow

```text
Developer
     │
     ▼
Write Code
     │
     ▼
Push Code to Git Repository
     │
     ▼
Continuous Integration
(Build + Test)
     │
     ▼
Continuous Delivery
(Package & Validate)
     │
     ▼
Continuous Deployment
(Deploy to Server)
     │
     ▼
Monitor Application
```

---

